          "body": "Three times in verses 3-4, David protests that his suffering is undeserved: 'not for my transgression nor for my sin... for no guilt of mine.' This is not self-righteousness; it is a specific forensic claim about this situation. David is not denying that he is a sinner in the absolute sense — Psalm 51 prevents that reading entirely. He is asserting that in the particular matter of Saul's pursuit, he has done nothing to deserve assassination. The claim is legally precise and historically accurate: David had served Saul faithfully, had killed Goliath, had married Saul's daughter, had played the lyre to soothe Saul's tormented mind. The Psalms grant the believer the right to claim innocence in specific situations before a God who is the just Judge. This is not self-justification before a human court; it is honesty before the Divine Witness who alone can verify the claim."
