          "body": "The dog imagery of verses 6-7 and 14-15 is one of the most deliberate rhetorical acts in the psalm. In the ancient Near East, the pariah dog was not a companion but a feral scavenger — associated with corpses, blood, nocturnal menace, and social degradation (1 Kings 14:11; 21:19; 22:38). To compare Saul's assassins to dogs is to strip them of the dignity they claim and place them beneath the notice of the God who 'scoffs at all the nations' (v. 8). The repetition of the image verbatim in verse 14 is structural, not redundant: both stanzas of the psalm open with the same threat, but the second time the reader encounters the howling pack, they have already heard God's laughter at them (v. 8) and David's resolve to watch for the Stronghold (v. 9). The pack is no less dangerous on its second circuit; the psalmist's soul is simply better positioned to see them clearly."
